{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a57102e2-fbd2-4a09-bb2b-aeef0effd48c","content":"TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively, so you need the `--treenode-filter` syntax:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nThis uses TUnit's tree-node path filter where `/**/SmsNotificationTests/**` matches all tests under the `SmsNotificationTests` class. The `**` wildcards match any namespace prefix and any test method underneath.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ce2b8201-3900-486e-8867-91ea4c85b607","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For MTP-based test runners, the filter syntax is different from VSTest.\n\nFor TUnit with MTP, to filter by class name, you use `--treenode-filter`:\n\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nThe treenode filter uses a path-like syntax where `/**` is a recursive wildcard.\n\nLet me confirm - TUnit 0.6.120 uses MTP. The project has `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>` which is typical for MTP-based test projects.\n\n\nSo the command to run just the SmsNotificationTests class would use that treenode filter syntax with the recursive wildcard pattern.","outputTokens":303,"requestId":"4C16:1E6FAE:85546F:A529D3:6A0131D4"},"id":"14a17381-332d-4347-9510-c544894bee57","timestamp":"2026-05-11T01:33:16.624Z","parentId":"ac825491-f73f-4160-9557-de7814080f96"}
